<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I estimate annual heating cost?", answer: "Multiply your design heat loss (BTU/hr at design outdoor temperature) by 24 hours and by heating degree days (HDD), then divide by the design temperature difference (indoor minus outdoor at design conditions). The result is annual delivered energy in BTU. Divide by the fuel heat content × efficiency to get fuel consumption, then multiply by unit cost." },
  { question: "What are heating degree days (HDD)?", answer: "HDD is the number of degrees a day's average temperature falls below 65 °F, summed over the heating season. A day averaging 40 °F has 25 HDD. An average US city like Chicago has 6,000 HDD per year; Miami has under 150; Minneapolis has 7,500; Anchorage has 10,500. Look up your local value from the NOAA Climate Data Online tool or your utility's website." },
  { question: "What efficiency should I use?", answer: "For furnaces and boilers, use the AFUE rating: 80% for mid-efficiency, 95-98% for condensing. For heat pumps, use the seasonal COP × 100 as efficiency: COP 2.5 = 250%, COP 3.5 = 350%. Electric resistance is 100%. Wood stoves are 60-75% (EPA certified). Fireplace inserts 60-70%." },
  { question: "Which fuel is cheapest for heating?", answer: "Depends heavily on local prices. Natural gas at $1.50/therm with 95% AFUE is typically $16/MMBTU delivered. Propane at $3/gal with 95% AFUE is $35/MMBTU. Heating oil at $4/gal with 87% AFUE is $33/MMBTU. Electric resistance at $0.15/kWh is $44/MMBTU. A heat pump with COP 3.0 at $0.15/kWh is only $15/MMBTU — cheapest in most areas." },
  { question: "How accurate is the HDD method?", answer: "Very good for mid-size heating costs over a full season — within 10-15% for most houses. Inaccurate for very tight modern houses (internal gains become relatively more important), very large houses with zoned heating, or houses with non-standard setpoint patterns. For critical projects use full hourly simulation (e.g., BEopt, EnergyPlus)." }
]) %>

